Independent economist Julian Jessop said there was no “hard evidence” of real economic damage caused by Brexit, meaning those who still regret the result are opting to turn to “dubious tactics” in order to make the case for greater alignment with the Brussels bloc. Writing in the Telegraph, he spotted at least seven, including the cherry picking of data, failing to compare like for like, for instance with growth statistics given countries starting lower down have “more scope to catch up”, and “dodgy ‘counterfactual’” models which “fail any reasonable smell test”. Mr Jessop argued that “rather than undermining the result of the 2016 referendum and thwarting Brexit, the priorities should be to fix the things that are going wrong.” FOLLOW BELOW FOR LIVE UPDATE…